14/12/2005
ANKARA, Turkey -- Turks have become more active in defending basic human rights, the country's Human Rights Directorate said Wednesday (14 December).
The office, which reports directly to the prime minister, said it had received 1,730 complaints about alleged rights violations in the first nine months of 2005, compared to 1,213 complaints in the same period last year.
In other news, some of the most renowned names in literature issued a statement of support for their Turkish colleague Orhan Pamuk, who faces criminal charges over remarks concerning the so-called Ottoman Empire's Armenian genocide.
His trial is scheduled to start Friday.
Authors Jose Saramago, Gabriel Garcia Marquez and Guenter Grass signed the statement.
(AFP, New TV - 14/12/05;
NTV - 13/12/05)
